body:
/kind feature

**Description**

I have been taking great advantage of the podman remote capability, and corresponding podman socket/service, using the podman connector for ansible.  This is much nicer than running remote ssh commands manually.  Many thanks for the work that has been done for this.

What I have noticed is that after my playbook has finished there can be in some cases hundreds of sleeping processes on the remote system whose child processes are long gone having only existed for a moment.  This appears to be done in the name of Docker compatibility.

The following code can be found in [pkg/api/handlers/compat/exec.go](https://github.com/containers/podman/blob/main/pkg/api/handlers/compat/exec.go#L74-L76)
```
        // Run the exit command after 5 minutes, to mimic Docker's exec cleanup
        // behavior.
        libpodConfig.ExitCommandDelay = 5 * 60
```

This is implemented in conmon [src/ctr_exit.c](https://github.com/containers/conmon/blob/main/src/ctr_exit.c#L201-L204) as
```
        if (opt_exit_delay) {
                ndebugf("Sleeping for %d seconds before executing exit command", opt_exit_delay);
                sleep(opt_exit_delay);
        }
```

I would like to request a feature to add some configuration to override the hard-wired code so that I could set a shorter delay in my podman systemd units, or in some similarly reasonable manner.  I am also wondering if this is even a behavior we want to mimic in this fashion.  Do we really need to do nothing for all that time?  Could we break out of the sleep when all the child processes are gone, poll in a loop with shorter sleeps, etc?

Thank you for your consideration of this request.
